    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-11-30T23:55:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-11-30T23:55:00-05:00" n="811"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d811">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94111/101: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Roosevelt</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName type="venue">U. S. S. “<hi
                                rend="smallcaps">Potomac</hi>”</placeName>,] <date
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1937-11-30T23:55:00">November 30, 1937—11:55
                            p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 1—1:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>0030. Think it best to send the neutrality proclamation for me to sign so that
                    there will be no delay.</p>
                <p>I take it that only the regular list of munitions will be based [<hi
                        rend="italic">barred?</hi>] from export but suggest immediate study of other
                    articles so that we can discuss advisability of enlarging list later on. I think
                    we should seek in every way possible to avoid helping one side and not the
                    other.</p>
                <p>Please advise what probable effect declaration of war will have on our Shanghai
                    and Tientsin position, also what is new from British angle.</p>
                <closer>[<signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Franklin</hi> D. <hi rend="smallcaps">Roosevelt</hi>
                    </signed>]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
